Motherhood

A new campaign highlights the stark reality of the UK’s paternity leave system – and why more must be done

By Georgia Green

2 days ago

2 min read

Pregnant The Screwed and The Dad Shift today launch a new campaign that highlights the stark reality of a two-week paternity leave system when the recovery time for a C-section is at least six weeks.

Giving birth is an overwhelming, life-changing event, but when you add complications like emergency caesareans to the mix, the recovery time, both physically and emotionally, is even longer.

In fact, doctors advise six weeks of recovery time for a C-section – and yet statutory paternity leave in the UK is just two weeks. With 42% of babies now delivered by C-section, that means 230,000 mums are left to recover alone while single-handedly caring for a newborn. Furthermore, 20,000 mums have self-employed partners who get no paid leave whatsoever.

It’s with this in mind that Pregnant Then Screwed and The Dad Shift have launched a new campaign that highlights this concerning issue. The campaign will see billboards and social media images of women bravely sharing pictures of their C-section scars branded with stickers that say ‘Paternity leave is a motherf**ker’, in a bid to drive home just how harrowing it can be to be left stranded while still recovering.

Statutory paternity leave in the UK is just two weeks

“Women have been paying the price of rubbish paternity leave for decades,” says Rachel Grocott, CEO of Pregnant Then Screwed. “We need to make parental leave make sense. We need to give dads and partners decent leave, to match that of mums, and we need to pay it properly too. Asking parents to survive on parental pay that is significantly below the national living wage is inhumane – you’d think the government has too many babies, not that we have a birth rate crisis, given how little support there is to help people to become parents today.”

George Gabriel, co-founder of The Dad Shift, agrees: “It’s hard to put into words just how shit it feels as a dad, knowing you can’t be there for your partner as they care for your baby while recovering from major surgery. The UK’s rubbish paternity offer means over 230,000 mothers are left every year to fend for themselves and their babies during their post-operative recovery because their partners are forced back to work… Evidence shows that where parents are given more parental leave, they experience lower levels of post-partum depression and lower wage gaps.”
